passages.text: While we are always sad to see Labor Day come and go, as it signals the unofficial end of summer, we are excited for the Fall conference season, which kicks off this week with our \(17^{\text{th}}\) Annual Real Estate Conference. Over the \(2\frac{1}{2}\) day period, we will hear from a few dozen companies on the latest Q3 trends but more importantly how things are shaping up for growth in 2026. While no company will give a full roadmap for earnings growth next year, we do expect to get some breadcrumbs from a host of REITs, and below we outline the major focal points for each panel we are hosting on Wednesday.

1. Transaction Panel - Where are marginal borrowing costs today and are buyers sitting on the sidelines waiting for the Fed to lower rates before accelerating their buying activity? Secondly, how are lenders viewing the office sector today in terms of willingness to make fresh loans?

2. Retail Panel - How are retailers changing their store opening plans, if at all, due to rising rents (look at ULTA's latest results) and higher tariffs which could begin to impact retail sales later in '25 and 1H26? Where does the watchlist of tenants sit today vs., say, 6 months ago?

3. Residential Panel - The main focus is the pace of new rent growth in light of the early end to Spring leasing and the slowdown in job growth. The other issue is the recent uptick in new starts and how that trend unfolds over the next year as the industry expects a big acceleration in rents by '27.

4. Fireside Chat - Our discussion with Blackstone and Brookfield should yield a lot of interesting datapoints on where capital is flowing, the appetite from institutional investors to grow their CRE footprints and the arbitrage between public and private markets.

5. Office Panel - Without question, the main issue is the pace of new leasing and whether it's sufficient to drive occupancy gains in '26 & '27, as this has been the industry's Achilles heel the past few years. The other focal point is the NYC vs. SF debate and whether New York is losing any leasing momentum due to the Mayor uncertainty and whether SF has enough demand to finally drive vacancy rates down.
6. Industrial Panel - With demand weak in Q2, investors are focused on this trend QTD and how it's impacting rent growth and whether rents stop falling moving into 2026.
7. Healthcare Panel - Life Science demand will be a focal point as XBI has quietly been rising as should demand for AL / IL product and the trends around pricing & margins.

Sector Performance Last Week & YTDWhile the final week of August is typically slow, there was some notable corporate news out last week in REIT- land, including a relatively wide bidding pool for Paramount (PGRE) per an article in the Real Deal and that shot the stock up well past \(\) 7\$ per share. In addition, REXR saw some news about a potential activist and that got industrial REITs moving on the day of the news. While tech earnings were strong last week, the S&P 500 actually closed down 10bp on the week while the REIT index rose \(1.0\%\) although YTD the RMZ is still lagging behind by 730bp.

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:

Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances. Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories. For this purpose, and in the Evercore ISI ratings distribution below, our Outperform, In Line, and Underperform ratings can be equated to Buy, Hold and Sell, respectively.
